Prior to Dempsey's 1970 kick, the longest field goal in NFL history was 56 yards, by [[Bert Rechichar]] of the [[1953 Baltimore Colts season|Baltimore Colts]] {{nowrap|in [[1953 Baltimore Colts season|1953]].<ref name=dfgwgmms/><ref name=cjbrs>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=E5ExAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OxAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2279%2C3321799 |work=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Colts jolt Bears, 13-9, get record 56-yard field goal |date=September 28, 1953 |page=2, part 2}}</ref>}} A 55-yard field goal, achieved by a [[drop kick]], was recorded by [[Paddy Driscoll]] in {{nfly|1924}}, and stood as the unofficial record until that point; some sources indicate a 54-yarder by [[Glenn Presnell]] in {{nfly|1934}} as the {{nowrap|record,<ref name=cjbrs/>}} due to the inability to precisely verify Driscoll's kick.

In a pre-season NFL game between the [[2002 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] and the [[2002 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] on August 29, 2002, [[Ola Kimrin]] kicked a 65-yard field goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=5739850|title=Living With 63 Yards – And Beyond|publisher=ESPN|date=November 4, 2010|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref>  However, because pre-season games are not counted toward official records, this accomplishment is not the official record.

