===CFL===
Because the goalposts in Canadian football are on the goal line, and because downing the ball in the end zone results in the kicking team scoring a [[single (Canadian football)|single point]], field goal returns are much more common. The longest missed field goal return in the CFL is 131 total yards. Against the [[Montreal Alouettes]] on August 22, 1958, the [[Toronto Argonauts]]' Boyd Carter ran 15 yards, then threw a lateral to [[Dave Mann (American football)|Dave Mann]], who then returned it for the final 116 yards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cflapedia.com/records.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150513204431/http://www.cflapedia.com/records.htm |archivedate=May 13, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> This return, which started 21 yards behind the goal line, was during the era of 25-yard end zones (which made the maximum theoretical missed field return distance 134 yards in those days) and therefore cannot be met or exceeded on the modern field with 20-yard end zones. Since the shortening of the end zones in the CFL in 1986, a field goal has been returned for the maximum 129 yards on four occasions: by [[Bashir Levingston]] of the Toronto Argonauts on June 28, 2007,<ref>{{YouTube|Qouhh-gA08Y}}</ref> by [[Dominique Dorsey]] also of the Toronto Argonauts on August 2, 2007,<ref>{{cite video|date= |title=Dominique Dorsey's record tying missed field goal return for a touchdown vs. the Montreal Alouettes |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zTv_oE-3fls |format=Video |medium= |publisher= |location=}}</ref> by [[Tristan Jackson]] of the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]] on July 14, 2012 <ref>http://cfl.ca/video/index/id/76119</ref> and by [[Trent Guy]] of the Montreal Alouettes on September 23, 2012.<ref>http://cfl.ca/article/hes-the-guy-129-yard-touchdown-seals-win-for-als</ref>

===NCAA===
In [[NCAA]] college football, only five missed field goals returns for touchdowns have ever been returned 100 yards or more:<ref name="Four returned missed field goals">{{cite web |url= http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/college/how-rare-missed-field-goal-returned-touchdown/nb8mB/|title=How rare is missed field goal returned for touchdown?|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref>
*September 17, 1966: Don Guest ([[California Golden Bears football|California Golden Bears]]), 108-yard return for a touchdown after a failed 47-yard field goal attempt by [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State]].<ref name="Four returned missed field goals"/>
*September 28, 1968: Richie Luzzi ([[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson Tigers]]), 108-yard return for a touchdown after a failed 47-yard field goal attempt by [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]].<ref name="Richie Luzzi return">{{cite web |url= http://espn.go.com/blog/sec/post/_/id/25390/yards-to-glory-sec-version|title=Yards to Glory, SEC version|work=ESPN|first=Chris|last=Low|date=August 1, 2011|accessdate=December 1, 2013}}</ref>
*September 7, 2013: [[Odell Beckham Jr.]] ([[2013 LSU Tigers football team|LSU Tigers]]), 109-yard return for a touchdown after a failed 59-yard field goal attempt by [[2013 UAB Blazers football team|UAB]].<ref name="Four returned missed field goals"/>
*November 30, 2013: [[Chris Davis (cornerback)|Chris Davis, Jr.]] ([[2013 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]]), 109-yard return for a touchdown after what would have been a tie-breaking 57-yard field goal attempt by [[2013 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] fell short as time expired, what some writers and fans call [[Kick Six|the greatest play in college football history]].<ref name="WBUR article">{{cite web |url=http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2013/12/02/auburn-alabama-game|title=Auburn-Alabama: The Greatest Play in College Football History?|work=Here&Now|first=John|last=Bacon|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name="New York Post article 2">{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2013/11/30/an-ending-well-never-forget/|title=Auburn-Alabama is greatest ending in sports history|work=New York Post|first=Mike|last=Vaccaro|date=November 30, 2013|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Huffington Post article">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/quora/is-the-2013-iron-bowl-ala_b_4372765.html|title=Is the 2013 Iron Bowl (Alabama vs. Auburn) the Most Dramatic Finish to a Football Game of All-Time?|work=Huffington Post|first=John|last=DeMarchi|date=December 2, 2013|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name="New York Daily News article">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/college/lupica-auburn-alabama-talked-article-1.1533789|title=End of Auburn vs. Alabama is one second in college football that will be talked about forever|work=New York Daily News|first=Mike|last=Lupica|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref>
*September 3, 2016: Brandon Wilson ([[2016 Houston Cougars football team|Houston Cougars]]), 109-yard return for a touchdown after a failed 53-yard field goal attempt by [[2016 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/playbyplay?gameId=400869507|title=Oklahoma vs. Houston - Play-By-Play - September 3, 2016 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2016-09-05}}</ref>

===U Sports===
In U Sports football, like in the CFL, the longest possible missed field goal return is 129 yards, and this has occurred three times.<ref name="CIS Football Records"/>

* Jeremy Botelho of the [[Manitoba Bisons]] playing against the [[Simon Fraser Clansmen]] on September 11, 2009
* Jedd Gardner of the [[Guelph Gryphons]] playing against the [[McMaster Marauders]] on October 8, 2010
* Tunde Adeleke of the [[Carleton Ravens]] playing against the [[Ottawa Gee-Gees]] on October 5, 2013

